Plotting logarithmic functions

In general, plotting logarithmic functions are similar to plotting exponentials as they are the inverse functions. However, in some cases they behave slightly differently. Suppose that we wish to plot a general exponential function \(f(x) = k \cdot \log_b(a-c) + d\). This is the general logarithmic function. We can see using the applet above that all logarithmic functions follow a similar shape, so in order to accurately sketch such graphs we need to find the following information:

  1. What happens to the function \(f(x)\) as \(x \to \pm\infty\)?
  2. What is the \(x\)-intercept of the graph?
  3. We need two different points to draw the curve.

We shall see this by way of the following example.

 

Example

Sketch the graph of \(y = \log_2(x-1)+1\) and state the domain and range of the function.

Solution

Firstly note that \(x-1>0\) when \(x>1\). Therefore

Domain: \(\{x: x> 1\}\).

Range:\(\{y : y \in \mathbb{R}\}\).

 

Next note that as \(x \to 1\) \(y \to -\infty\), therefore the vertical line which the graph tends to is \(x = 1\), this is the vertical asymptote of the graph. Also note that as \(x \to \infty\), \(y \to \infty\), so there is no horizontal asymptote. In addition, if \(x = 0\) then \(\log_2(x-1)\) is undefined, so there is no \(y\)-intercept.

To find the \(x\)-intercept we set \(y = 0\) and rearrange the function to get \(x\). therefore, we have \[ 0 = \log_2(x-1)+1 \implies \log_2(x-1)= -1 \implies x-1 = 2^{-1} = \frac{1}{2} \implies x = \frac{3}{2}. \] So the \(x\)-intercept is \(\frac{3}{2}\).

Now let us find two points on the curve, say \(x = 2\) and \(x = 5\). Then \[ x = 2 \implies y = \log_2(2-1)+1 = 1 \qquad \mbox{ and } \qquad x = 5 \implies \log_2(5-1)+ 1 = 2+1 =3. \] Therefore two points are the curve are \((2,1)\) and \((5,3)\). Putting all of this together we can sketch the following graph.


As a summary, we can see that the function \(f(x) = \log_a x\) has the following properties:

  1. Domain: \(\{x: x> 1\}\).
  2. Range:\(\{y: y \in \mathbb{R}\}\).
  3. Asymptote: \(x = 1\) (vertical).
